definition.value: 46C is an embryonic stem cell line, constructed in the laboratory of Austin Smith, in which a drug resistance gene is placed under the control of a Sox1 promoter.  Cells were isolated from the 129a mouse strain. [PMID: 12524553]
ES-cells isolated from C57BL/6xCBA
Fetal myoblast Desmin+
organ producing either sperm or ova
Neuron class of two pharyngeal neurosecretory-motor neurons.
type of cells that make up muscle layers in the pharynx in worms such as C. elegans
C. elegans at 20 Centigrade: 0-24 hours after L4-adult molt

C. elegans 520-620min after first cleavage at 20 Centigrade. Cell number remains at ~560 cells, with some new cells generated and some cells go through programmed cell death. The shape of embryo is elongated and tripple fold. A stage between 2-fold embryo and fully-elongated embryo. Also called pretzel embryo or pretzel stage.
C. elegans 20-40min after first cleavage at 20 Centigrade. Contains 4 cells.
C. elegans 0-350min after first cleavage at 20 Centigrade. Proliferate from 1 cell to 560 cells. From start of first cleavage till cleavage is over.
C. elegans 210-350min after first cleavage at 20 Centigrade. Proliferate from 421 cells to 560 cells. The stage before the fast cleavage of cells finishes.
C. elegans 100-290min after first cleavage at 20 Centigrade. Proliferate from 28 cells to 421 cells. Referring to the whole period of gastrulation.

C. elegans 620-800min(hatch) after first cleavage at 20 Centigrade. Cell number remains at ~560 cells, with some new cells generated and some cells go through programmed cell death. A stage after elongation is over. The last stage of embryogenesis. Also called pre-hatched embryo, late embryo or morphogenetic embryo.
C. elegans 290-350min after first cleavage at 20 Centigrade. Proliferate from 421 cells to 560 cells. The stage when embryo just finished gastulation and is enclosing.

C. elegans 350-620min after first cleavage at 20 Centigrade. Cell number remains at ~560 cells, with some new cells generated and some cells go through programmed cell death. The stage that embryo starts elongation till elongation is over.
C. elegans third stage larva specialized for dispersal and long term survival.
C. elegans first stage larva. At 25 Centigrade, it ranges 14-25.5 hours after fertilization, 0-11.5 hours after hatch.
C. elegans fourth stage larva. At 25 Centigrade, it ranges 40-49.5 hours after fertilization, 26-35.5 hours after hatch.
C. elegans stage when the larval shifts from L2d larva to dauer larva. It includes the synthesis of new cuticle, cease of phrayngeal pumping during a lethargus stage, and the shed off of old cuticle.
C. elegans stage right after a larva recovered from dauer but has not started transformation to L4 larva yet.
quantification of the level of estrogen receptors in a tumor
quantification of  progesterone receptors in breast cancer. PR status is used in the classification of breast cancers.

quantification of the level of human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2) in a tumor. Amplification or overexpression of the HER2 oncogene plays a role in the development and progression of some breast cancers.
RIP-Chip refers to the immunoprecipitation of RNPs from cell extracts and the subsequent microarray analysis of associated RNA molecules.
Describes the procedure whereby biological samples for an experiment are sourced.
Describes the procedure which dissects biological materials into anatomical sub-components, e.g. specific organs or tissues.
describes the procedure for dissection.

Describes the conversion of samples (e.g. RNA samples) to another form (e.g. complementary DNA) with no prior dedicated extraction step of the former form, and no labeling of the converted product with chemical tags or dyes during the process. Other examples of such conversions are bisulphite conversion for DNA methylation analysis, various RNA modifications prior to immunoprecipitation.
The technology type or platform of the reporters on the array.
Controlled terms for descriptors of types of array substrates.
Controlled terms for descriptors for coating of the substrate.

physiological response of an organism, eg in terms of flushing, to consuming alcohol
quantification of the volumetric fraction of blood pumped out of the left and right ventricle with each heartbeat or cardiac cycle
quantification of the content of parasites in the blood, used as a measurement of parasite load in the organism and an indication of the degree of an active parasitic infection

value.value: A disease of the cardiac muscle developed subsequent to the initial protozoan infection by trypanosoma cruzi. After infection, less than 10% develop acute illness such as myocarditis (mostly in children). The disease then enters a latent phase without clinical symptoms until about 20 years later. Myocardial symptoms of advanced chagas disease include conduction defects (heart block) and cardiomegaly.

definition.value: a form of cardiomyopathy that develops as a result of Chagas disease, an infection with the protozoan parasite Trypanosoma Cruzi
Trypanosoma cruzi seropositivity is the result of a measurement of circulating T. cruzi specific antibodies

value.value: A vascular reaction of the skin characterized by erythema and wheal formation due to localized increase of vascular permeability. The causative mechanism may be allergy, infection, or stress.

definition.value: Urticaria is a kind of skin rash notable for pale red, raised, itchy bumps that might also cause a burning or stinging sensation. It is often but not necessarily caused by an allergic reaction.
Condition similar to urticaria but with swelling occuring in a lower layer of the dermis as well as in the subcutis.

value.value: Swelling involving the deep dermis, subcutaneous, or submucosal tissues, representing localized edema. Angioedema often occurs in the face, lips, tongue, and larynx.

definition.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory.

label.value: delayed encephalopathy after acute carbon monoxide poisoning

value.value: Anoxic encephalopathy resulting from acute CO intoxication, developing within 2-6 weeks of the poisoning event

definition.value: anoxic encephalopathy resulting from acute CO intoxication, developing within 2-6 weeks of the poisoning event
A vial is a unique aliquot of biological material e.g. iPSC.

Quantification of the fraction of nitric oxide in the total exhalation volume, used as a non-invasive biomarker of eosinophilic airway inflammation. Higher Feno values are associated with childhood asthma symptoms, exacerbations, physician-diagnosed asthma and atopy.
